          "sectionId": "call-of-duty-free",
          "title": "The Grand Tour: Travel as a Rite of Passage",
          "guidingSection": "Call of Duty-Free",
          "rawOfficialText": "The rise of hotels coincided with the rise of tourism—travel for leisure, instead of for migration or business. Historians trace the roots of modern tourism to the grand tours of the 17th and 18th centuries, in which young aristocrats would travel across Europe as a rite of passage. Review a typical grand tourist itinerary, then discuss with your team: in what sense does this tradition continue today?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Historic UK — The Grand Tour",
              "url": "https://www.historic-uk.com/CultureUK/Grand-Tour/"
            },
            {
              "label": "ThoughtCo — The Grand Tour of Europe",
              "url": "https://www.thoughtco.com/grand-tour-of-europe-1435014"
            },
            {
              "label": "Britannica — Grand Tour",
              "url": "https://www.britannica.com/topic/grand-tour"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "In the 17th and 18th centuries, many wealthy young British aristocrats took a long European journey called the Grand Tour. It was meant to complete their education by exposing them to language, art, classical ruins, manners, diplomacy, and elite social life. The typical route moved from Britain to France and then into Italy, with major stops such as Paris, Lyon, Venice, Florence, Rome, and Naples. The Grand Tour helps students see one of the birthplaces of modern tourism: travel was no longer only for business, migration, war, or pilgrimage. It became a cultural experience, a rite of passage, and a way of shaping identity and status.\n\nAdd the social map: the Grand Tour was mainly a wealthy British rite of passage in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, moving through France and Italy and sometimes the Low Countries or German states. It turned travel into education, status, language practice, art collecting, and social networking, which is why it belongs between schooling, tourism, and adulthood. Use this to connect travel with support systems: what moves, where it pauses, how services or hubs make movement possible, and why arrival depends on many places that are not the destination.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows how travel became educational, cultural, and social rather than only practical. At the section level, it explains why hotels and tourism developed together: once travel became desirable in itself, systems grew to host and guide travelers. At the year-theme level, it connects to “Are We There Yet?” because the Grand Tour turns the journey itself into the point: the traveler is not only trying to arrive somewhere, but to be changed by the road.",
          "takeaway": "Many travelers still use travel to gain culture, identity, memories, status, and personal growth",
          "subjects": [
            "History"
          ],
