          "title": "When Is It Wise to Let Go?",
          "guidingSection": "Concluding Questions",
          "rawOfficialText": "When is it a good idea to give up? Be sure to learn about the sunk cost fallacy. Does it imply that we should quit on things more often? How about on people?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "The Decision Lab - The Sunk Cost Fallacy",
              "url": "https://thedecisionlab.com/biases/the-sunk-cost-fallacy"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "The sunk cost fallacy happens when people keep investing time, money, effort, or emotion into something mainly because they have already invested so much. That can make quitting feel like wasting the past, even when continuing would create more stress or harm. This entry asks students to separate wise persistence from irrational attachment: sometimes “not giving up” is courage, but sometimes letting go is the clearest decision.\n\nAdd the decision frame: sunk cost is about refusing to waste the past, even though only future costs and future benefits can still be changed. Students should test each case by asking whether continuing serves a real goal, protects a person, or only keeps an old promise alive because quitting feels embarrassing. Use this to return to the theme: what counts as arrival, when waiting or quitting becomes reasonable, how closure changes a story or decision, and why getting there often opens another question.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand that stopping can be a serious decision, not just failure. At the section level, it turns the theme’s final questions toward judgment: when is a destination no longer worth the route? At the year-theme level, it connects to endings and progress because choosing to stop can itself become a threshold, a reset, or the start of a better path.",
          "takeaway": "Stopping can be rational when the future no longer justifies the cost",
