          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The UCLA article and podcast are not just support sources: they change the way the entry should be taught. They show adolescence as an evolutionary and cross-species stage of exploration, learning, dispersal, status sensitivity, risk, and plasticity. That means adolescence should not be framed only as a modern human problem or a defective half-adult brain.\nThe Scientific American link is central for the keyword slides. It explains the adolescent brain as adaptable and still under construction, with the prefrontal cortex maturing later than reward and emotion systems. This helps students understand risk-taking as a mismatch and an opportunity, not just stupidity.\nThe KidsHealth brain-development page is useful for visuals because it provides teen-friendly diagrams of the prefrontal cortex and related brain areas. It should guide image choice for the prefrontal cortex slide.\nThe raw Britney Spears line should be used as a hook only: she was 20, so the entry is deliberately separating teenager from adolescent. The real lesson is that adolescence is biological and developmental, while teenager is a modern social/cultural label.",
          "studentExplanation": "Adolescence is not just a modern human invention. The UCLA links show that many animals also pass through a risky, flexible learning stage between childhood and adulthood, when they explore, leave safe places, learn social rules, and test themselves. The newer part is the teenager as a social identity: a visible age group shaped by school, youth culture, spending money, music, media, and modern expectations. Even the famous idea that the brain is “finished at 25” is too simple: brain development is gradual, uneven, and shaped by experience.\n\nThe notes add an important correction to the “brain finished at 25” shortcut: adolescent development involves pruning, integration, segregation, white matter connections, and social learning across a flexible range, not one magic birthday. The modern teenager is newer than adolescence itself because school, consumer culture, music, media, and youth identity made that stage visible. Use this to connect biology, language, and culture: what transition is happening, when society recognizes it, how people perform or resist maturity, and why growing up rarely matches one clean age line.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this separates three ideas students often mix together: puberty, adolescence, and teenager identity. At the section level, it opens Going Pains by showing that growing up is biological, social, linguistic, and cultural all at once. At the year-theme level, adolescence is a classic threshold: a person is no longer simply a child, but not yet fully settled into adult roles.",
