          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The links are the actual raw content here. The entry has little meaning without the works, because each work gives a different model of the messy middle: rebellion, inherited responsibility, classroom innocence fading, uncertainty after conflict, forced adaptation, escapist belonging, and restart after damage.\nWe Real Cool should be taught as compressed teenage bravado racing toward consequences. The shortness and repeated “we” make identity feel collective, performative, and fragile.\nThe Medicine Bag and St. Lucy’s Home for Girls Raised by Wolves are crucial because they complicate growth: becoming older may mean carrying heritage, adapting under pressure, or being split between worlds, not simply “finding yourself.”\nIn Mrs. Tilscher’s Class should anchor the transition from childhood security to adolescent awareness. It is especially useful because the imagery turns classroom comfort into heat, curiosity, and storm-like change.\nThe video/song links should remain in the app as media content, not citations. Where Do We Go From Here? and Lost Boy let students hear uncertainty and escape rather than only read about them.",
          "studentExplanation": "The works in this entry do not present adulthood as one clean step. They show rebellion, embarrassment, inherited responsibility, classroom innocence fading, forced adaptation, escape, and the wish to begin again. Together, they make adolescence feel like a messy middle space where childhood and adulthood overlap. The linked poems, stories, and songs are not optional support: they are the content students need to explore in order to understand the entry.\n\nUse the literature and songs as different models of messiness rather than as a single message. Brooks, Sneve, Duffy, Miranda, Springsteen, and the other works show rebellion, shame, family duty, classroom innocence, performance, and escape, so students should ask what each text thinks growing up costs. Use this to connect biology, language, and culture: what transition is happening, when society recognizes it, how people perform or resist maturity, and why growing up rarely matches one clean age line.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see that art often captures growing up better than a definition can. At the section level, it gives emotional depth to Going Pains: growing up is something people feel, perform, resist, and survive. At the year-theme level, the entry asks whether adulthood is a destination someone reaches or a role someone slowly learns to wear.",
          "takeaway": "Adulthood can feel like roles learned through mistakes",
