          "sectionId": "home-and-wandering",
          "title": "Wayfinding Without Screens",
          "guidingSection": "Home and Wandering",
          "rawOfficialText": "“We know where we are,” sang Moana’s ancestors—and they knew it without maps, compasses, or access to Starlink. Instead, Polynesians drew on a complex system of non-instrument navigation, including the star compass, ocean swells, and animal sightings. In the Arctic, the Inuit use the night sky and other markers to find their way—even in a landscape almost uniformly white with ice and snow. With your team, explore traditional navigation methods (including some that may be legendary) and consider: how does the journey change if the map is not on our screen but in our mind? Would the world be better off if more people knew how to navigate it without their phones?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Polynesian wayfinding - Hōkūleʻa",
              "url": "https://hokulea.com/polynesian-wayfinding/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Arctic Wayfinders - Terrain.org",
              "url": "https://www.terrain.org/2019/nonfiction/arctic-wayfinders/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Did Vikings navigate by polarized light? - Scientific American",
              "url": "https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/did-vikings-navigate/"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The Hōkūleʻa link is the core content source for Polynesian non-instrument navigation: it grounds the entry in real wayfinding systems such as star compass knowledge, swell patterns, wind, clouds, birds, and careful memory. The Moana link is useful as an accessible cultural doorway, but the Hōkūleʻa page should carry the explanation so the app does not treat Disney as the authority.\nThe Arctic Wayfinders article is extremely rich and should shape the slideshow. It explains Inuit navigation as learned environmental literacy: snowdrifts, currents, sounds, animal movement, atmospheric effects, cairns/inuksuit, oral knowledge, sketch maps, and driftwood/tactile maps. The Viking link is different: it should be framed as possible/legendary navigation, not as fully settled fact.",
          "studentExplanation": "Wayfinding without screens is not guessing. Polynesian navigators read stars, swells, winds, birds, clouds, and memory across huge ocean distances, while Inuit travelers read snow, ice, sound, currents, cairns, animal movement, and story-linked landmarks in the Arctic. The links matter because they show navigation as a relationship with the world: the map can live in the body, memory, elders, and environment, not only on a phone.\n\nThe supplemental sources make traditional navigation feel practical rather than mystical: Polynesian navigators read stars, swells, winds, birds, and clouds; Inuit travelers used memory, landmarks, snow, and local knowledge; Viking sunstone stories point to polarized light. No-screen navigation is still data, just not a phone map. Use this to track movement beyond simple maps: what is guiding the traveler, where the threshold or border sits, how tools, animals, memory, or law shape arrival, and why being near home is not always the same as belonging.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students respect traditional navigation as skilled knowledge rather than “primitive” travel. At the section level, it deepens Home and Wandering by contrasting device-based navigation with attention-based navigation. At the year-theme level, it asks whether “getting there” changes when the route is something you know, feel, and remember rather than something an app displays.",
          "takeaway": "Wayfinding can live in memory, story, body, sky, ice, wind, and practiced attention.",
