          "title": "Reaching the Border Is Not the Same as Being Accepted",
          "guidingSection": "Home and Wandering",
          "rawOfficialText": "Immigrants by land and sea can also face obstacles to entry when they reach their destinations. Consider the case of the St. Louis, a ship carrying Jewish refugees from Nazi Germany in 1939. The passengers were denied entry in the United States, Canada, and Cuba, and many ultimately died in Nazi concentration camps. More recently, the United States has stopped allowing people to ask for asylum at its southern border; European countries are also increasingly reluctant to accept refugees. Explore the reasons behind these anti-immigrant policies; do some make more sense than others? Then, discuss with your team: how open should countries be to those arriving at their borders in dire need? Should there be limits on the number admitted, and, if so, how should those limits be calculated?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "The St. Louis refugee ship - HISTORY",
              "url": "https://www.history.com/articles/wwii-jewish-refugee-ship-st-louis-1939"
            },
            {
              "label": "Migration and European politics - Axios",
              "url": "https://www.axios.com/2018/08/24/migration-drives-populist-surge-across-europe"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The St. Louis link is the moral center of the entry. It turns border policy from an abstract debate into a concrete historical tragedy: Jewish refugees fleeing Nazi Germany reached the Americas, were denied entry by multiple countries, and many later died after being forced back into Europe. The point for students is that arrival can fail at the threshold.\nThe modern-policy side should be handled carefully and neutrally. Anti-immigrant policies can be defended through arguments about capacity, security, law, and political stability, but the St. Louis case warns that border decisions can have life-or-death consequences. The slideshow should make the comparison without pretending all historical and current cases are identical.",
          "studentExplanation": "Arriving at a border is not the same as being welcomed through it. The St. Louis case shows this in the most tragic way: people fleeing Nazi Germany reached possible safety, but the United States, Canada, and Cuba refused them, and many later died in the Holocaust. Modern asylum and refugee debates are different in context, but they raise the same threshold question: when people arrive in danger, how do states balance law, capacity, fear, responsibility, and human need?\n\nThe St. Louis and migration poems show that arrival has two layers: reaching a place and being recognized by that place. Borders are not just lines on maps; they are decisions made by states, publics, documents, ships, ports, and the stories countries tell about welcome. Use this to track movement beyond simple maps: what is guiding the traveler, where the threshold or border sits, how tools, animals, memory, or law shape arrival, and why being near home is not always the same as belonging.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows that borders are decisions, not just map lines. At the section level, it deepens Home and Wandering by showing that wandering can end at a closed threshold. At the year-theme level, it asks whether “getting there” matters if the destination refuses to let you belong.",
          "takeaway": "A border is not only a line on a map; it is a moral threshold that decides who may enter.",
          "subjects": [
            "Social Studies"
          ],
