          "title": "Simba, Teenagers, and Life in the In-Between",
          "guidingSection": "Introductory Questions",
          "rawOfficialText": "\"I just can’t wait to be king,\" complains Simba. He is not quite one thing, not quite another. Not everyone is the heir to the throne, but we do all spend time as teenagers, no longer children but not yet adults. Are there advantages to life in the in-between? Would it be better if we transitioned more quickly from childhood to adulthood?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Disney+ — The Lion King official page",
              "url": "https://www.disneyplus.com/movies/the-lion-king/1HqwiEcje6Nj"
            },
            {
              "label": "Disney song guide — I Just Can’t Wait to Be King",
              "url": "https://disneynews.us/disney-song/i-just-cant-wait-to-be-king-song/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "“I Just Can’t Wait to Be King” comes from Disney’s The Lion King, with music by Elton John and lyrics by Tim Rice. Young Simba imagines kingship as freedom: no orders, no supervision, everyone admiring him. Zazu’s interruptions matter because they reveal what Simba does not yet understand: power also means responsibility, patience, and care for others. That is why the song fits adolescence. Teenagers are no longer small children, but they are not fully adult either; they are in a threshold stage where freedom, identity, and responsibility are being learned unevenly. The entry asks whether the in-between is wasted delay or a necessary space for practice before real consequences arrive.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this gives students a familiar example of liminality. At the section level, it links the introduction to Going Pains and the wider theme of thresholds. At the year-theme level, it asks whether time spent in-between is a problem to escape quickly or a necessary space for growth, practice, and identity.",
          "takeaway": "He is between childhood and expected responsibility",
          "subjects": [
            "Lit & Media"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Thresholds & Irreversibility",
            "Delayed Arrival",
            "Narrated Endings",
            "Infrastructure Shapes Behavior"
          ],
