          "title": "Technologies That Seemed Close but Never Arrived",
          "guidingSection": "Introductory Questions",
          "rawOfficialText": "Are there lessons we can learn from technologies that once seemed about to arrive—nuclear-powered cars, food pills, 3D televisions, and many more—but haven’t yet?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Smithsonian — Visions of nuclear-powered cars",
              "url": "https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/visions-of-nuclear-powered-cars-captivated-cold-war-america-but-the-technology-never-really-worked-180985437/"
            },
            {
              "label": "The Henry Ford — Ford Nucleon artifact",
              "url": "https://www.thehenryford.org/collections-and-research/digital-collections/artifact/278186"
            },
            {
              "label": "IEEE Spectrum — Why 3-D TV failed",
              "url": "https://spectrum.ieee.org/3d-tv-is-officially-dead-for-now-and-this-is-why-it-failed"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "This entry is about futures that looked close because they matched the dreams of their moment, then failed when reality pushed back. Nuclear-powered cars came from the Atomic Age optimism of the late 1950s and early 1960s, with concept models such as the Ford Nucleon, Studebaker-Packard Astral, Arbel Symétric, and Seattle-ite XXI promising extreme range or futuristic travel. The problem was not imagination but practicality: reactors were too large, shielding too heavy, waste unresolved, and costs unsafe for ordinary cars. Food pills also sounded efficient in science fiction, feminism, population anxiety, and the space-race imagination, but pills cannot replace the calories, fiber, volume, and pleasure of meals. 3D television shows a third pattern: a technology can work technically and still fail if it is expensive, inconvenient, uncomfortable, or not useful enough.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this teaches students to question predictions instead of simply believing them. At the section level, it gives the introduction a bridge into futurism. At the year-theme level, it connects to prediction and progress by showing that some futures remain “almost there” because imagination moves faster than real-world adoption.",
          "takeaway": "Prediction needs reality checks about use, risk, and adoption",
