          "title": "Vibe Coding and the Flood of New Software",
          "guidingSection": "Monkey See, Monkey Prototype",
          "rawOfficialText": "In the world of software, AI-powered vibe coding allows users to create programs without writing a line of code. Just ask a chatbot for what you want and watch it appear. You might want to try vibe-coding yourself, then discuss with your team: should we be worried about a future flooded with too many programs of uncertain quality and with limited support? Is it better if not everyone can get “there” so easily?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "What vibe coding is",
              "url": "https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/vibe-coding"
            },
            {
              "label": "AI coding risk / quality concern",
              "url": "https://www.techtarget.com/searchsecurity/tip/Vibe-coding-security-risks-and-how-to-mitigate-them"
            },
            {
              "label": "Example of AI-assisted app building",
              "url": "https://replit.com/ai"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Vibe coding means using AI tools to create software from natural-language instructions instead of writing every line by hand. This can help beginners build quickly and make software creation feel more open. But it also creates a quality problem: if many people can generate apps without understanding the code, the result may be buggy, insecure, unsupported, or hard to maintain.\n\nThe sources frame vibe coding as code-first, refine-later prototyping. It lowers the barrier to making an app, but students should ask who understands the result, who maintains it, what bugs are hidden, and whether speed has replaced responsibility. Use this to judge readiness: what kind of model is being shown, how close it is to the final thing, where humans or assumptions are hidden, and why a prototype can both teach and mislead.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see that easier creation is not automatically better creation. At the section level, it shows how prototypes can now appear extremely quickly in software. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress and prediction because easier tools may speed up innovation while also flooding the world with weaker products.",
          "takeaway": "Easy software creation still needs quality control, maintenance, and support.",
