          "sectionId": "monkey-see-monkey-prototype",
          "title": "Humans Behind the Curtain",
          "guidingSection": "Monkey See, Monkey Prototype",
          "rawOfficialText": "Some companies have even sold products and services that still secretly relied on people to function properly. Amazon’s AI-powered cashiers at their “Just Walk Out” grocery stores were actually overseen by thousands of low-paid workers; Fireflies.ai makes millions a year selling automated notetaking at meetings, but recently revealed that at first their powerful AI was just the founders listening in and writing stuff down. Look for similar cases, then discuss with your team: should companies be punished for releasing successful products and services that once relied on human intervention but no longer do? Is “fake it ’til you make it” justified as long as you make it in the end?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Amazon Just Walk Out reporting",
              "url": "https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2024/04/amazon-ends-ai-powered-store-checkout-which-needed-1000-video-reviewers/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Amazon response / clarification",
              "url": "https://apnews.com/article/amazon-just-walk-out-india-checkout-160bf03c1654f665834ab141e6db7516"
            },
            {
              "label": "Fireflies.ai early human-note-taking report",
              "url": "https://futurism.com/artificial-intelligence/fireflies-founder-startup-ai"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Some products are sold as automated even though humans still help them work behind the scenes. Sometimes that human help is temporary while the company builds better technology. Sometimes it becomes a trust problem because users, workers, or investors may not understand what is really happening. This entry asks whether “fake it till you make it” is a clever bridge to the future or an unfair way to sell a product that is not what it seems.\n\nThe extra notes connect Amazon Just Walk Out and early Fireflies-style support to hidden labor. The key question is not only whether a product uses AI, but where human review, annotation, correction, or manual work enters the system and whether customers are allowed to know. Use this to judge readiness: what kind of model is being shown, how close it is to the final thing, where humans or assumptions are hidden, and why a prototype can both teach and mislead.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand hidden labor inside supposedly automated systems. At the section level, it connects prototypes, human support, and misleading appearances. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress because some products reach the market while still depending on invisible help.",
          "takeaway": "Human-supported AI needs honesty about its limits, labor, and level of automation.",
