          "sectionId": "more-to-do-than-can-ever-be-listed",
          "title": "A Brief on To-Do Lists",
          "guidingSection": "More To Do Than Can Ever Be Listed",
          "rawOfficialText": "Things to do today include exploring the history of the to-do list (alternate link). You will find that they were famously used by Benjamin Franklin and Leonardo da Vinci, among other high achievers of history. Below are some more modern approaches to to-do lists to explore - or even try. Which format seems best to you?\nEisenhower Method | 1-2-3 Method | Ivy Lee Method | 4-D Method | Eat that Frog | Must-Do | Bullet Journal",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "History of the to-do list - The Atlantic",
              "url": "https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2012/02/a-brief-history-of-the-to-do-list-and-the-psychology-of-its-success/252826/"
            },
            {
              "label": "History of the to-do list - archived alternate link",
              "url": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120215211320/https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2012/02/a-brief-history-of-the-to-do-list-and-the-psychology-of-its-success/252826/"
            },
            {
              "label": "The Marginalian - A Brief History of the To-Do List and the Psychology of Its Success",
              "url": "https://www.themarginalian.org/2012/02/09/willpower-to-do-list/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "The main idea is not simply \"make a list.\" A list can turn a big, confusing goal into smaller, clearer steps, but only if it helps you decide what matters most. The history link shows that people have long used lists to manage unfinished work, from famous historical figures to modern productivity systems. The Eisenhower Method sorts tasks by urgency and importance; the 1-2-3 Method limits the day to one big task, two medium tasks, and three smaller tasks; Ivy Lee reduces the next day to a short ranked list; the 4-D Method forces a choice between doing, delaying, delegating, or deleting; Eat That Frog says to start with the hardest important task; Must-Do / MoSCoW separates essential tasks from optional ones; and Bullet Journal turns lists into a flexible personal tracking system. Together, these systems show that planning is not about doing everything. It is about choosing a route through too much to do.\n\nAdd the practical methods as contrasting designs: Eisenhower sorts urgency and importance, Ivy Lee limits the day to six tasks, 1-2-3 balances big and small work, 4-D separates do/delay/delegate/delete, Eat That Frog attacks the hard task first, and Bullet Journal uses rapid logging to lower friction. Use this to distinguish planning from completion: what the list records, where attention gets stuck, how a method changes behavior, and why unfinished work keeps returning to the mind.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand that a to-do list is a way of transforming mental clutter into visible steps. At the section level, it opens More To Do Than Can Ever Be Listed by showing that progress often begins with deciding what not to do. At the year-theme level, it connects to planning and progress because a list is a small map of a journey: it does not guarantee arrival, but it makes movement easier to see.",
          "takeaway": "It makes progress visible while forcing choices",
