          "sectionId": "more-to-do-than-can-ever-be-listed",
          "title": "Umberto Eco, the To-Do List Specialist",
          "guidingSection": "More To Do Than Can Ever Be Listed",
          "rawOfficialText": "“The list is the origin of culture,” the writer Umberto Eco once said. He held an exhibit of lists at the Louvre (which should have improved security on its own to-do list); he compiled a book on the topic, too. Learn about Eco’s distinction between practical and poetic lists and consider - what kind of list is a to-do list? Then discuss with your team: are we more drawn to lists than we should be?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Umberto Eco and lists - The Guardian",
              "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/dec/12/umberto-eco-lists-book-review"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Umberto Eco’s idea is that lists do more than organize chores. In The Infinity of Lists, he distinguishes between practical lists and poetic lists. Practical lists are useful and limited: shopping lists, schedules, inventories, guest lists, and to-do lists help people organize real life. Poetic lists are more imaginative: they can suggest abundance, wonder, excess, or something too large to fully contain. A to-do list is mostly practical, but it can also become strangely poetic when it grows endlessly and starts to represent a whole life of unfinished goals. Eco’s point helps students see that lists are not only productivity tools; they are one way humans try to make order inside infinity.\n\nEco’s point is bigger than errands. Lists can organize culture, imagination, collecting, knowledge, and infinity; they let people handle things too large to hold in memory. Students should compare practical lists, poetic lists, museum-like lists, and impossible lists that reveal desire more than completion. Use this to distinguish planning from completion: what the list records, where attention gets stuck, how a method changes behavior, and why unfinished work keeps returning to the mind.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand that list-making belongs to culture, literature, and philosophy as much as to productivity. At the section level, it completes More To Do Than Can Ever Be Listed by showing the double nature of lists: they can help us act, but they can also reveal that there is always more to do. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress and planning because lists are small attempts to answer “Are we there yet?” in a world where the answer is often “not yet, and maybe never completely.”",
          "takeaway": "Lists help humans order abundance and imagine infinity",
          "subjects": [
            "Lit & Media"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Incompletion That Stays Active",
            "Visible vs Real",
            "Infrastructure Shapes Behavior",
            "Managing Uncertainty"
          ],
