          "title": "What 2018 Thought 2028 Would Look Like",
          "guidingSection": "Next Year in Futurism",
          "rawOfficialText": "With apologies to Mr. Armstrong, sometimes people also predict too much for the next ten. Consider these predictions for the year 2028, made in 2018. Are there any that haven’t come true yet but that you think still might in the next two years?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Kindred Capital - Take me to the Year 2028",
              "url": "https://kindredcapital.medium.com/take-me-to-the-year-2028-1dd405bd30b6"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "A 2018 forecast for 2028 is useful not because it gives a perfect map of the future, but because it reveals what investors and technology thinkers thought was accelerating at that moment. The article predicts a new mobile form factor, major autonomous-car adoption, a huge freelance workforce, longer lives, security drones, mainstream vegetarianism, cashless payment, solar growth, enhanced athletes, VR addiction, and more Brexit talks. Students should treat the article as a time capsule: some predictions were directionally smart, some were too fast, and some reveal the hopes and fears of 2018 more than the reality of 2028.\n\nTreat the 2018 forecast as a time capsule, not just a checklist. It predicted new phone forms, autonomous miles, freelancers, cashless payments, VR addiction, wireless charging, and altered sports; the useful exercise is to ask which predictions failed because the tech was hard, and which failed because people did not adopt them. Use this to audit promises: what future is being predicted, when people expected it, how technical or social limits delayed it, and why “soon” can be a feeling rather than a calendar date.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this teaches students to evaluate predictions after time has passed. At the section level, it gives a concrete forecast to test rather than abstract futurism. At the year-theme level, it connects to prediction and progress because the future is partly imagined from the anxieties, investments, and blind spots of the present.",
          "takeaway": "Predictions are also documents of the present that produced them",
