          "sectionId": "next-year-in-futurism",
          "title": "Future Promises and the Problem of Timing",
          "guidingSection": "Next Year in Futurism",
          "rawOfficialText": "Tesla is far from the only person to have declared that “it will soon be possible…” Sentences that begin with this and similar phrases (e.g., “In a few years, everyone will…”) almost always make ambitious predictions about the near future. Search online for examples like them, then discuss with your team: for each one, are we there yet, and how long did it take us to get there? If not, how close are we? Here are three examples to get you started.\n\n“…for one man to be heard by every human being on Earth” (1925)\n“…to launch a satellite that makes its own solar array in orbit” (2019)\n“…for humans to live a thousand years or more” (2025)",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Gartner - Hype Cycle explanation",
              "url": "https://www.gartner.com/en/research/methodologies/gartner-hype-cycle"
            },
            {
              "label": "Our World in Data - Technology adoption",
              "url": "https://ourworldindata.org/technology-adoption"
            },
            {
              "label": "Pew Research Center - Internet and technology reports",
              "url": "https://www.pewresearch.org/topic/internet-technology/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Futurist language often sounds precise while remaining vague. Phrases like “soon,” “in a few years,” and “everyone will” turn uncertainty into confidence. Sometimes the prediction is not completely wrong: the technology arrives later, smaller, more unevenly, or in a form people did not expect. This entry trains students to read prediction language carefully and ask what exactly is being promised: technical possibility, mass adoption, cheap access, legal permission, or cultural acceptance.\n\nUse this as a forecast-audit tool. Students should ask what would have to exist for a promise to arrive: materials, cost, laws, public trust, maintenance, energy, training, and demand. A technology can be invented and still not be socially ready. Use this to audit promises: what future is being predicted, when people expected it, how technical or social limits delayed it, and why “soon” can be a feeling rather than a calendar date.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, students learn that prediction is partly language analysis. At the section level, this moves futurism beyond gadgets and into rhetoric. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress because “Are we there yet?” often depends on whose timeline is being sold.",
          "takeaway": "Prediction requires evidence about systems, not only ideas",
          "subjects": [
            "Special Area"
          ],
