          "studentExplanation": "Life-extension futurism mixes serious biology with extreme fantasy. The overheard Putin-Xi conversation about organ transplants and living to 150 makes the topic political as well as scientific: longer life is not just a medical dream, but also a question of power, inequality, and who gets access. Some technologies aim to repair tissues, slow cell damage, or replace organs. Others, like cryonics or digital immortality, ask whether preserving a body or data would really preserve a person. The strongest question is not only “Can humans live longer?” but “What kind of world would be created if only some people could?”\n\nThe sources make longevity a stack of partial tools: organ transplants require rejection management, edited pig organs and stem cells are experimental, organoids model organs rather than replace full bodies, and bioprinting still struggles to create working tissues at scale. The ethical question is who gets more life, not just whether more life is possible. Use this to audit promises: what future is being predicted, when people expected it, how technical or social limits delayed it, and why “soon” can be a feeling rather than a calendar date.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see life extension as science plus ethics. At the section level, it turns futurism inward toward the body and identity. At the year-theme level, it connects to bright/dark futures because longer life can sound hopeful, unfair, frightening, or politically dangerous depending on who benefits.",
          "takeaway": "Whether longer life would be safe, fair, meaningful, and desirable",
