          "sectionId": "the-lovely-and-the-liminal",
          "title": "The Doorway Effect",
          "guidingSection": "The Lovely and the Liminal",
          "rawOfficialText": "You’re there now—but why? If you’ve ever forgotten why you walked into a room, you may have experienced what scientists call the doorway effect. This temporary amnesia happens when you pass through the threshold of a liminal space; scientists theorize that the brain may “reset” short-term memories when it finds itself in a new setting. Liminality is that state of being in-between: you aren’t where you were but you’re also not where you’re going. As you explore this concept, discuss with your team: what are other examples of liminal spaces and thresholds in our own lives?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Doorway effect - Scientific American",
              "url": "https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/why-walking-through-doorway-makes-you-forget/"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The Scientific American article is not just a citation: it supplies the core mechanism. In the experiment, participants remembered carried objects less accurately and more slowly after passing through a doorway than after walking the same distance in the same room. The important idea for students is not “doors are magic”; it is that the brain organizes experience into event models, and a new setting can tell the mind that the previous event is less relevant.\nThis makes the entry stronger than a metaphor. Liminality is usually poetic or cultural, but this link gives it a cognitive basis: thresholds can change what the mind keeps active.",
          "studentExplanation": "The doorway effect is the familiar moment when you enter a room and suddenly forget why you came there. The Scientific American link matters because it explains an experiment: people remembered less well after crossing a doorway, even when the distance walked was the same. That suggests a threshold can act like a mental boundary. Liminality is therefore not only an artistic mood; it can be a real cognitive experience, where the brain treats a new place as a new “event.”\n\nThe doorway effect is useful because it makes liminality cognitive, not just aesthetic. A threshold can divide memory into events, so walking through a door may prompt the brain to update context and drop the previous intention. Use this to test the word “liminal” carefully: what threshold is present, where movement pauses, how the space changes memory or feeling, and whether the in-between is useful, beautiful, scary, or too vague.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this gives students a concrete everyday example of liminality. At the section level, it opens The Lovely and the Liminal by showing that the in-between can affect memory, attention, and focus. At the year-theme level, it connects to thresholds because “getting there” can change what we remember from “back there.”",
          "takeaway": "A threshold can change what the mind keeps active.",
