          "sectionId": "theres-a-draft-in-here",
          "title": "Music Is Also a Creative Process",
          "guidingSection": "There’s a Draft in Here",
          "rawOfficialText": "In songwriting, early drafts are called demos. Sometimes, the songwriter will perform them him or herself, even if the song is intended for someone else to sing. Consider the following demos and then the finished product, then ask yourself: what changed along the way? What makes the finished product feel more “done”?\n\nThe Beatles | “Strawberry Fields Forever (Home Demo Sequence)” (1966)\nLin-Manuel Miranda | “This One's Mine” (2018)\nSophia Anne Caruso | “Dead Mom (Demo)” (2019)\nEJAE | “Golden” (various demos) (2025)",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "The Beatles: Strawberry Fields Forever (home demo sequence)",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jD2h0WuQ9kE&list=RDjD2h0WuQ9kE&start_radio=1"
            },
            {
              "label": "The Beatles: Strawberry Fields Forever (final version)",
              "url": "https://youtu.be/HtUH9z_Oey8?si=7-0x6i8ovFsCI7CB"
            },
            {
              "label": "Golden: EJAE and Mark Sonnenblick explain the process",
              "url": "https://youtu.be/FxEX_GWwE7M?si=Pba2OEygGxpnTVEU"
            },
            {
              "label": "Golden: finished movie version",
              "url": "https://youtu.be/yebNIHKAC4A?si=tzRmEZd1VLfwnuMl"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Songs also have drafts. A demo can reveal a song before it has its final voice, arrangement, production, or scene placement. Comparing the Beatles’ home demo of Strawberry Fields Forever with the final version shows how a raw musical idea can become a studio-built atmosphere. The Golden process links show another path: a song for a film can pass through songwriting, story needs, production, performance, and approval before the short final track feels inevitable. In music, the draft is often audible: you can hear what changed.\n\nA demo is not just a worse version; it is evidence of a decision path. Strawberry Fields, Hamilton drafts, Dead Mom, and Golden show lyrics, arrangement, character, production, and story needs changing before a song feels final. Use this to make process visible: what changed between versions, where the earlier form still survives, how revision altered meaning, and why a “finished” work often hides many unfinished stages.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students hear drafting as a creative process, not only see it in visual art. At the section level, it expands There’s a Draft in Here from canvases to songs, demos, producers, and performers. At the year-theme level, it connects to planning and prototypes because a song may spend a long time being “almost there” before it becomes the version everyone knows.",
          "takeaway": "Music lets us hear creativity moving from rough possibility to chosen form",
          "subjects": [
            "Art & Music"
          ],
