          "sectionId": "theres-a-draft-in-here",
          "title": "Never Released... Until the Internet Allowed It",
          "guidingSection": "There’s a Draft in Here",
          "rawOfficialText": "In musical theatre, not all demos end up in the final product - but the Internet has allowed these unproduced numbers to find an audience. Consider the following demos that never quite got there. For each, discuss with your team: why do you think it was left out of the finished product?\n\nAladdin | “Count on Me” (1994)\nPocahontas | “First to Dance” (1995)\nBook of Mormon | “Family Home Evening” (2009)\nDear Evan Hansen | “In the Bedroom Down the Hall” (2017)",
          "rawOfficialBullets": [
            "Most performers rehearse before they go on stage; some people even rehearse before difficult conversations. Investigate the psychology of rehearsal. What parts of the brain does it affect? How do you know when you’ve rehearsed enough?"
          ],
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Aladdin - Count on Me",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W9ePWzAxO-s"
            },
            {
              "label": "Pocahontas - First to Dance",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r_j4ALKLrOk"
            },
            {
              "label": "Book of Mormon - Family Home Evening",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=txG99YiQcNk"
            },
            {
              "label": "Dear Evan Hansen - In the Bedroom Down the Hall",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cvf1ETgCMN4"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Many drafts disappear before the public ever sees them, but music and theatre have become easier to archive, upload, and rediscover. Cut songs are especially interesting because they are not always bad songs. Sometimes the story changes, the tone changes, the pacing improves without them, or the final structure needs a different emotional focus. “Count on Me,” “First to Dance,” “Family Home Evening,” and “In the Bedroom Down the Hall” all show that creative work can be complete enough to exist, but still not fit the destination the final production chooses.\n\nCut songs are especially useful because they may be complete but still not belong. Aladdin, Pocahontas, The Book of Mormon, and Dear Evan Hansen examples show that deletion can be about pacing, tone, plot focus, or replacement rather than quality alone. Use this to make process visible: what changed between versions, where the earlier form still survives, how revision altered meaning, and why a “finished” work often hides many unfinished stages.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand why unfinished or unreleased creative work matters. At the section level, it closes There’s a Draft in Here by showing that some drafts never reach the official final product, but still reveal the path that production took. At the year-theme level, it connects to drafts, prototypes, and endings because some works remain permanently in-between: made, revised, even loved, but not finally included.",
          "takeaway": "Unreleased material can reveal the creative decisions behind the final version",
          "subjects": [
            "Art & Music"
          ],
