          "title": "Projects That Took Too Long to Get There",
          "guidingSection": "We're All in This to Get There",
          "rawOfficialText": "As returning scholars might remember, some big projects take much too long to finish - high speed rail in California, the Haunted Chocolatier, these outlines. Some never get there at all. Explore the following examples of projects that were not finished on time, then discuss with your team: What factors, if any, did these delays have in common? How would you have overcome them? And are there projects out there in the world today that you predict will suffer a similar fate?\n\nLa Sagrada Familia | Spain\nNusantara Capital City | Indonesia\nRyugyong Hotel | North Korea\nWonderland Amusement Park | China\nBerlin Brandenburg Airport | Germany\nMilan Cathedral | Italy\nCrazy Horse Memorial | South Dakota",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "La Sagrada Familia - Guinness World Records",
              "url": "https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2025/1/oldest-active-construction-project-la-sagrada-familia-to-finish-in-2026"
            },
            {
              "label": "Nusantara Capital City - Asia Times",
              "url": "https://asiatimes.com/2025/12/indonesias-new-capital-falls-victim-to-the-politics-of-forgetting/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Crazy Horse Memorial - Business Insider",
              "url": "https://www.businessinsider.com/crazy-horse-monument-isnt-finished-70-years-on-photos-2019-9"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Some big projects become famous because the finish line keeps moving. La Sagrada Familia, Nusantara, Ryugyong Hotel, Wonderland, Berlin Brandenburg Airport, Milan Cathedral, and Crazy Horse Memorial each show a different reason why a project can remain unfinished or arrive very late: funding gaps, political change, technical systems, symbolism, design changes, land disputes, cultural controversy, or simply the enormous scale of the goal. This entry asks students to compare delays as patterns, not just as amusing failures.\n\nThe source examples give different kinds of delay: Sagrada Familia mixes faith, design, war, and scale; Nusantara depends on politics and logistics; Ryugyong Hotel reflects economic crisis; Berlin Brandenburg shows system failure; Crazy Horse raises symbolism, labor, and controversy. Use this to connect ambition to coordination: what the project is trying to finish, where time and resources break down, how tools make work visible, and why people remain the hardest part of planning.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see delay as a structural problem, not just bad luck. At the section level, it opens We are All in This to Get There by showing why project management matters: large ambitions can easily slip when many people, institutions, materials, and expectations must align. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress and delay because some destinations are so large that getting there becomes a multi-generation struggle.",
          "takeaway": "Large projects are shaped by systems of ambition, money, politics, design, and time",
