          "title": "How Parking Took Over the Landscape",
          "guidingSection": "Where the Sidewalk Starts",
          "rawOfficialText": "Many sidewalks have cars parked alongside them. There are at least a billion parking spots in the United States alone - three times as many as there are people. With your team, investigate the history of parking, then discuss with your team: should people have a right to free parking at their homes and places of work?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "History of parking - NPR / Fresh Air",
              "url": "https://www.npr.org/2023/05/09/1174962751/paved-paradise-examines-how-parking-has-changed-the-american-landscape"
            },
            {
              "label": "Paved Paradise transcript mirror - CapRadio",
              "url": "https://www.capradio.org/news/npr/story?storyid=1174962751"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Parking can look like a small personal convenience, but at city scale it becomes a huge design system. When a society builds enough spaces to store cars at homes, jobs, shops, stadiums, and streets, it quietly reshapes land values, sidewalks, housing, traffic, and expectations. The key question is not just “Where should drivers park?” It is “Who pays for parking when it is called free, and what else could that land have become?”\n\nThe added frame is land use. “Free” parking still costs land, housing, walking space, taxes, and urban attention; the real question is what a city stops becoming when so much of it is reserved for cars waiting between trips. Use this to read infrastructure as a design choice: what space is being created, where pedestrians or cars are placed, how movement changes, and who gains or loses from that layout.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see parking as a policy choice rather than a natural right. At the section level, it connects sidewalks to car storage and public space. At the year-theme level, it connects to thresholds because parking lots and curb spaces are in-between places: not destinations, but powerful structures that shape how every journey begins and ends.",
          "takeaway": "Parking is a design and policy choice that reshapes public expectations and urban form",
          "subjects": [
            "Social Studies"
          ],
