          "title": "When Parking Lots Become Architecture",
          "guidingSection": "Where the Sidewalk Starts",
          "rawOfficialText": "People usually park their cars and then dash on to their destination as quickly as they can; they may not give the parking lot itself a second glance. Liminal spaces are easy to overlook on your way to somewhere else. But some parking lots are self-conscious architectural masterpieces. Read about the Temple Street Parking Garage in New Haven - and then look into these other lots below. Should more parking lots be built with this much architectural flourish, or should they be as invisible as possible?\n\nLego Parking House | Billund, Denmark\nParc des Celestins | Lyon, France\nMichigan Theater | Detroit, Michigan\nGaragenatelier Car Park | Herdern, Switzerland\n9th Avenue Parkade | Calgary, Canada",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Temple Street Parking Garage",
              "url": "http://hiddenarchitecture.net/temple-street-parking-garage/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Lego Parking House",
              "url": "https://www.dezeen.com/2019/12/23/lego-car-park-billund-denmark-cebra/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Parc des Celestins",
              "url": "https://en.visiterlyon.com/discover/heritage-unesco/contemporary/parking-des-celestins"
            },
            {
              "label": "Michigan Theater",
              "url": "https://weburbanist.com/2011/01/01/detroits-michigan-theater-the-worlds-most-beautiful-parking-lot/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Garagenatelier Car Park",
              "url": "https://www.ignant.com/2012/06/08/garagenatelier/"
            },
            {
              "label": "9th Avenue Parkade",
              "url": "https://www.fastcompany.com/90784597/today-its-a-multi-story-parking-lot-tomorrow-it-could-be-your-new-home"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Parking structures are usually treated as places to pass through quickly, but some are designed as serious architecture. Temple Street Parking Garage makes car movement visible in concrete; Lego Parking House turns a garage into brand-based urban design; Parc des Celestins hides a visual artwork inside an underground garage; Michigan Theater turns a former movie palace into a haunting parking space; Garagenatelier embeds garages into a Swiss hillside; and Calgary’s 9th Avenue Parkade was designed so it could one day adapt to other uses. Together, they show that even spaces meant for temporary storage can carry meaning, memory, and civic identity.\n\nUse the named garages as a design spectrum: Temple Street exposes movement, Lego Parking House turns storage into brand play, Parc des Celestins hides an artwork underground, Michigan Theater preserves a ghost of old entertainment, and Calgary designs for possible future conversion. Use this to read infrastructure as a design choice: what space is being created, where pedestrians or cars are placed, how movement changes, and who gains or loses from that layout.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students rethink functional spaces they normally ignore. At the section level, it deepens the idea that liminal spaces can be designed, not just tolerated. At the year-theme level, it connects to thresholds because a parking garage is usually between one place and another, yet it can still become a destination of attention.",
          "takeaway": "Even in-between utility spaces can carry beauty, memory, identity, and future possibility",
          "subjects": [
            "Art & Music"
          ],
