          "sectionId": "where-the-sidewalk-starts",
          "title": "What Is a Snout House?",
          "guidingSection": "Where the Sidewalk Starts",
          "rawOfficialText": "Many suburban homes don’t hide their parking lots at all - their garages are front-and-center. Consider these so-called “snout houses”, then discuss with your team: have you seen any in your community, and would it be better if their garages were more hidden?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Snout houses - Jalopnik",
              "url": "https://www.jalopnik.com/this-is-a-snout-house-the-mid-size-crossover-of-homes-1850736863/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "A snout house is a suburban home where the garage projects toward the street and becomes the most visible part of the front. Critics dislike this because the house seems to announce the needs of the car before the life of the people inside. But the debate is not one-sided: on small lots, a front-facing garage can be practical, affordable, and efficient. The real question is what a neighborhood communicates when the most public face of home is built around storage for vehicles.\n\nA snout house is a small architectural argument about priorities. When the garage dominates the street face, the home tells neighbors and pedestrians that car storage is the public front; the defense is practicality on small lots, but the cost is weaker street life. Use this to read infrastructure as a design choice: what space is being created, where pedestrians or cars are placed, how movement changes, and who gains or loses from that layout.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see that a home’s front design carries social meaning. At the section level, it moves the sidewalk discussion into suburban domestic architecture. At the year-theme level, it connects to home and thresholds because the garage can become the real “front door” of car-centered life.",
          "takeaway": "Domestic architecture can reveal whether a neighborhood is organized around cars or human street life",
          "subjects": [
            "Social Studies"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Infrastructure Shapes Behavior",
            "Visible vs Real",
            "Movement Without Arrival",
            "Thresholds & Irreversibility"
          ],
          "examples": [
            "The garage as the face of the house",
            "Car convenience versus street life"
          ],
          "debateRelevance": "Useful when debating whether suburban design should privilege cars, curb appeal, neighborhood life, or a balance among them.",
          "counterargument": "A prominent garage can be a practical response to everyday life rather than proof that a neighborhood has failed socially or aesthetically.",
