          "title": "Frank Lloyd Wright and the House Built Around the Car",
          "guidingSection": "Where the Sidewalk Starts",
          "rawOfficialText": "Modern architect Frank Lloyd Wright would certainly have hidden them: he imagined cars living inside of houses. For him, there was no need for wasted liminal space between homes and streets. Explore the design and history of his famous Robie House, then discuss with your team: does it truly “blur the boundaries between interior space and the world of nature”? How different would your school look if it had followed the same principles?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Frank Lloyd Wright and cars/houses",
              "url": "https://www.gearpatrol.com/archive/a177905/automotive-architecture-frank-lloyd-wright/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Robie House - Frank Lloyd Wright Trust",
              "url": "https://flwright.org/explore/frederick-c-robie-house"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Frank Lloyd Wright did not imagine the car as something that should simply shout from the front of the house. He wanted modern homes to absorb movement, landscape, and daily life into a more unified design. Robie House is important because it shows Wright’s Prairie-style idea of a building that stretches horizontally, connects interior and exterior, and feels rooted in its site. In this entry, the car is only part of the bigger question: should a home be a hard box separated from street and nature, or a flowing threshold between them?\n\nWright’s carport idea matters because he did not simply bolt a garage onto a house. He tried to integrate movement, shelter, landscape, and daily life, so the car became part of a wider architectural flow rather than the loudest object on the facade. Use this to read infrastructure as a design choice: what space is being created, where pedestrians or cars are placed, how movement changes, and who gains or loses from that layout.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this gives students a design alternative to the snout house. At the section level, it connects cars, garages, homes, sidewalks, and landscape into one architectural problem. At the year-theme level, it connects to liminality and thresholds because Wright’s work asks where the inside ends and the outside begins.",
          "takeaway": "Architecture can redesign thresholds between home, street, movement, and landscape",
          "subjects": [
            "Art & Music"
          ],
