          "sectionId": "where-were-going-well-still-need-them",
          "title": "Roads That Think, Charge, Heal, and Drain",
          "guidingSection": "Where We're Going, We'll Still Need Them",
          "rawOfficialText": "Modern engineering is moving towards roads that do more than just sit on the ground—they participate actively in transport. As you explore the innovations below, consider: what problems are they trying to solve, and what new ethical or environmental problems might they create? Ultimately, is the future of the road paved at all, or does something more radical await over the horizon?\n\nsolar roadways | piezoelectric materials | inductive charging\nDSRC | self-healing asphalt | modular pavement | permeable pavement",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "EPA permeable pavement",
              "url": "https://www.epa.gov/soakuptherain/soak-rain-permeable-pavement"
            },
            {
              "label": "ScienceDirect self-healing asphalt via induction",
              "url": "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S095006181933079X"
            },
            {
              "label": "TRB induction healing of porous asphalt",
              "url": "https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.3141/2305-10"
            },
            {
              "label": "DSRC overview",
              "url": "https://legalclarity.org/what-is-dsrc-dedicated-short-range-communications/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Dynamic wireless EV charging example",
              "url": "https://time.com/7094804/inductev-wireless-charging-network/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Future roads may not simply carry vehicles; they may generate energy, charge vehicles, communicate safety data, repair early cracks, or absorb stormwater. But a smarter road is not automatically a better road. Each innovation asks a trade-off question: does it actually solve a real problem at scale, or does it create new costs, surveillance concerns, repair burdens, and environmental risks?\n\nSmart-road ideas should be judged by maintenance and scale, not just novelty. Piezoelectric roads, inductive charging, DSRC, self-healing asphalt, modular pavement, solar surfaces, and permeable pavement each solve one problem while creating cost, durability, surveillance, or repair questions. Use this to treat roads as systems, not background: what the route is built to do, where it channels people or goods, how it changes choices, and why routes remain cultural even after their practical role changes.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand roads as active technologies rather than passive surfaces. At the section level, it moves the guiding section from road history to future infrastructure. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress because it asks whether the road to the future should be more technological, more resilient, or simply better maintained.",
          "takeaway": "Whether active infrastructure improves mobility enough to justify its trade-offs",
          "subjects": [
            "Science & Tech"
          ],
