          "studentExplanation": "In these works, the road is not just a surface under someone’s feet. It becomes longing, tiredness, freedom, exile, duty, temptation, memory, or fear. Some speakers choose movement; others are pushed by loss, duty, age, or restlessness. The road can promise adventure, but it can also reveal loneliness and the cost of leaving home.\n\nThe poems make the road psychological. Du Fu, Shakespeare, Masefield, Frost, and other road texts turn movement into longing, fatigue, choice, exile, duty, temptation, or memory, so students should ask what state of mind each road creates. Use this to treat roads as systems, not background: what the route is built to do, where it channels people or goods, how it changes choices, and why routes remain cultural even after their practical role changes.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students read roads as emotional symbols. At the section level, it shifts the guiding section from engineering to inner life. At the year-theme level, it connects to home, wandering, and thresholds because leaving the doorstep always means entering uncertainty.",
